==English==
===Etymology===
Late Latin ''[[anathema]]'' (a [[curse]], a person cursed, an [[offering]]) < Greek ''[[ανάθεμα]]'' (a [[votive offering]])< Greek ''[[anatithenai]]'' (to [[dedicate]])< Greek ''[[ana-]]'' ([[up]])< PIE ''[[*an-]]'' ([[on]]) + Greek ''[[tithenai]]'' (to put, to place)< PIE ''[[*dhe-]]''(to set, put). The Greek term was a [[calque]] on the Biblical Hebrew term ''[[herem]]''.

A term formerly indicating offerings made to the divinity which were suspended from the roof or walls of temples for the purpose of being exposed to view. Thus anathema according to its etymology signifies a thing offered to God. The word anathema is sometimes used in this sense in the Old (not in the original Hebrew) and New Testaments: because it was associated with setting apart (for God), it gradually came to have the meaning as set apart (from God).

===Noun===

'''anathema''' (plural '''anathamas''')

#A ban or curse pronounced with religious solemnity by ecclesiastical authority, and accompanied by excommunication. Hence: Denunciation of anything as accursed.
#An [[imprecation]]; a [[curse]]; a [[malediction]].
#Any person or thing anathematized, or cursed by ecclesiastical authority.
